"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528124","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-12-15","<p>The information requested for the MoJ is published in the department’s annual accounts. These can be found on gov.uk.</p><p>Data for core NOMS spending on consultancy can be found in the table below.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>NOMS Consultancy Spend</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011/2012</p></td><td><p>£6,473,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012/2013</p></td><td><p>£288,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013/2014</p></td><td><p>£217,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/2015</p></td><td><p>£1,881,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>As of 2015/16, NOMS consultancy spend is published in the annual report and accounts, which is available on gov.uk.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-12-15T17:52:43.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528124/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528124/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528124/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-06-20","National Offender Management Service: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much (a) National Offender Management Service (NOMS) and (b) his Department spent on external consultancy fees related to NOMS in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","41046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528125","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-09-01","<p>We only use temporary staff to fill business-critical posts and essential frontline services, where they can offer a fast, flexible and efficient way of providing skills not currently available in-house.</p><p> </p><p>The proportion of the department’s staff agency workers either covering operational uniformed staff of clerical agency staff is displayed in the following table. Data prior to 2011/12 is not available.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year-end date</p></td><td><p>Proportion of Operational Uniformed Staff</p></td><td><p>Proportion of Clerical agency staff</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31/03/2012</p></td><td><p>1.92%</p></td><td><p>0.58%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31/03/2013</p></td><td><p>2.03%</p></td><td><p>0.76%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31/03/2014</p></td><td><p>3.17%</p></td><td><p>1.14%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>31/03/2015</p></td><td><p>4.61%</p></td><td><p>1.61%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2016-09-01T11:27:40.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528125/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528125/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528125/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-06-20","Ministry of Justice: Temporary Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the Answer of 10 December 2015 to Question 18873, what proportion of his Department's staff were agency workers covering (a) operational uniformed staff and (b) clerical agency staff in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","40990"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528126","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-06-30","<p>The review we are currently undertaking on Employment Tribunals fees is assessing the impact that the introduction of fees has had on proceedings in the Employment Tribunals, including in relation to characteristics protected under the Equality Act 2010.</p><p> </p><p>We expect to announce the conclusion of the review in due course.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-06-30T15:21:48.943Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528126/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528126/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528126/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-06-20","Employment Tribunals Service: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the reasons for recent reductions in the number of cases brought by women in employment tribunals.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","40938"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528127","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-01","<p>There are currently no EU directives for which MoJ has responsibility awaiting transposition into UK law.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-07-01T13:55:26.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528127/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528127/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528127/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-06-20","Ministry of Justice: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what EU directives related to his Department's responsibilities are awaiting transposition into UK law.","false","Biography information for John Redwood","Wokingham","John Redwood","40891"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528128","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-07-01","<p>This Department is currently leading negotiations on the following legislative proposals:</p><ul><li>Proposal for a Council Decision on a Union position in the EU – the Republic of Albania Stabilisation Council on the participation of the Republic of Albania as an observer in the European Union Agency for Fundamental Rights’ work and the respective modalities, within the framework of Council Regulation (EC) No 168/2007.</li><li>Proposal for a Council Decision on a Union position in the EU – the Republic of Serbia Stabilisation Council on the participation of the Republic of Serbia as an observer in the European Union Agency for Fundamental Rights’ work and the respective modalities, within the framework of Council Regulation (EC) No 168/2007<em>.</em></li><li>Ongoing consideration of the European Union’s Accession to the European Convention of Human Rights following Opinion 2/13 of the CJEU.</li></ul><p>The following are ongoing negotiations within my department’s remit that the UK does not participate in. My department, however, monitors the negotiations to ensure that these proposals do not negatively impact UK interests.</p><ul><li>Council Regulation on Jurisdiction, Applicable Law and the Recognition and Enforcement of Decisions in matters of Matrimonial Property Regimes.</li></ul><ul><li>Council Regulation on Jurisdiction, Applicable Law and the Recognition and Enforcement of Decisions in matters of the Property Consequences of Registered Partnerships.</li></ul><ul><li>Directive on Provisional Legal Aid for Suspects or Accused persons Deprived of Liberty and Legal Aid in European Arrest Warrant Proceedings.</li></ul>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-07-01T13:55:29.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528128/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528128/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528128/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-06-20","Ministry of Justice: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, which EU (a) legislative and (b) other proposals his Department is leading negotiations on for the Government in the Council of the EU.","false","Biography information for John Redwood","Wokingham","John Redwood","40911"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528129","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-06-28","<p>The Working Group has now submitted its findings, which support the case for problem-solving courts.</p><p>Training of the judiciary is a matter for the judiciary and the judicial college. We will be working with both, taking learning from approaches nationally and internationally, as we progress our work on problem-solving courts.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","40865 ; 40866","2016-06-28T08:24:50.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528129/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528129/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528129/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-06-20","Courts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans his Department has for training the judiciary on the implementation of problem-solving courts.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","40864"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528130","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-06-28","<p>The Working Group has now submitted its findings, which support the case for problem-solving courts.</p><p>Training of the judiciary is a matter for the judiciary and the judicial college. We will be working with both, taking learning from approaches nationally and internationally, as we progress our work on problem-solving courts.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","40864 ; 40866","2016-06-28T08:24:50.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528130/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528130/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528130/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-06-20","Courts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many courts will be involved in the problem-solving courts pilot programme; and how much funding has been allocated to those pilots.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","40865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528131","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-06-28","<p>The Working Group has now submitted its findings, which support the case for problem-solving courts.</p><p>Training of the judiciary is a matter for the judiciary and the judicial college. We will be working with both, taking learning from approaches nationally and internationally, as we progress our work on problem-solving courts.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","40864 ; 40865","2016-06-28T08:24:50.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528131/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528131/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528131/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-06-20","Courts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when he expects the Problem-Solving Courts Working Group to (a) conclude and (b) report back on its work.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","40866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528132","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-06-30","<p>The review is assessing how successful the reforms had been in meeting their original objectives including, as far as we can, the impact of fees in relation to characteristics protected under the Equality Act 2010.</p><p>We are planning to announce the conclusions of the review in due course.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-06-30T15:28:25.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528132/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528132/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528132/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-06-20","Employment Tribunals Service: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of employment tribunal fees on the gender pay gap.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","40867"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528133","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-06-30","<p>HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service does not record the reasons why claimants withdraw their employment tribunal case.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-06-30T10:13:55.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528133/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528133/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528133/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-06-20","Employment Tribunals Service: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many employment tribunal claimants withdrew their case due to the requirement to pay fees (a) since 2013, (b) between April 2014 and March 2015 and (c) between April 2015 and March 2016.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","40868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528134","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-06-30","<p>The legal profession in England and Wales is independent from government. We want to see an innovative and competitive market that provides people with affordable legal services that they want and need, with regulation that supports the public and consumer interest.</p><p> </p><p>We welcome the Law Society’s survey and will take account of the findings as part of the development of legal services policy.</p><p> </p><p>The legal services regulators have a duty to promote the regulatory objectives set out in the Legal Services Act 2007, including improving access to justice and increasing public understanding of the citizen's legal rights and duties. The regulators have established the “Legal Choices” website, which provides people with information to help them in deciding whether and how to seek legal advice and the available services they might choose from. The Advicenow website, established by Law for Life, provides information on rights and the law.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","40870 ; 40871","2016-06-30T15:34:12.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528134/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528134/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/528134/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-06-20","Administration of Justice","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the findings of the Law Society's online survey of individuals' handling of legal issues in England and Wales 2015, published in May 2016.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","40869"
